Stucco painting might look simple on the surface, but anyone with experience knows it’s a different beast compared to painting wood or drywall. If you’re aiming for smooth, lasting results, you need more than just a brush and a bucket of paint—you need to understand the material. That’s why this guide on stucco painting will walk you through repair, prep, and paint, the right way.
Step 1: Inspect and Repair the Stucco Surface
Before you even think about painting, inspect your stucco carefully. Look for cracks, chips, or areas where the stucco has pulled away from the wall. Small hairline cracks can be filled with masonry caulk. For larger damaged areas, use stucco patching compound and apply it with a putty knife or trowel. Let it cure properly—this can take up to a few days depending on the patch size and weather.
Bonus tip: If your stucco has been previously painted, check for peeling or flaking areas. Scrape those off and sand the edges to smooth them out. Fresh paint needs a sound surface to stick.
Step 2: Clean and Prep the Wall
Next up: cleaning. Stucco’s rough texture traps dirt, dust, and mildew. Use a garden hose or pressure washer on a gentle setting to clean the surface. If there’s mold or mildew, scrub with a mixture of water and a little bleach, then rinse well. Let it dry completely—moisture trapped behind paint can lead to bubbling or peeling.
Once clean and dry, check if a primer is needed. If you’re painting new stucco, or going from a dark to light color, priming is essential. Use a masonry bonding primer designed for porous surfaces. This ensures the paint will stick properly and not soak right in.
Step 3: Choose the Right Paint and Tools
When it comes to painting stucco, elastomeric paint or high-quality acrylic latex is your best bet. These paints are flexible and can bridge hairline cracks while resisting harsh weather. Avoid cheap paints—they won’t last on a textured surface like stucco.
Use a roller with a thick nap (¾” to 1¼”) to reach into the texture, or a sprayer for large walls. Always back-roll with a roller to push paint into the grooves. Two coats are ideal for durability and even coverage.
Final Thoughts: Don’t Rush It
Painting stucco isn’t a job to rush. Each step—repair, prep, paint—affects how long your finish will last. Done right, a quality stucco paint job can last 10 years or more with minimal maintenance.
Whether you’re refreshing a faded exterior or protecting a new wall from the elements, following the right process gives you professional-looking, long-lasting results. That’s the beauty of understanding stucco painting—once you’ve mastered it, your walls don’t just look better; they last longer too.

